  "name": "Claude's internal processing steps",
  "summary": "**Conversation Overview**\n\nThe user asked Claude to locate a previous conversation where they had discussed the processes that Claude uses before going to the LLM. Claude used conversation search functionality to find relevant past discussions, searching with keywords like \"Claude processes LLM architecture pipeline.\" The search results revealed several conversations about dual-LLM systems and processing architectures, with the most relevant being the \"Eclissi Cure\" conversation from January 15. In that discussion, they had explored Luna's tiered routing system (T0-T4) which processes queries through different layers including Phi-3 for signal processing, SmolLM2 for reflexes, and Haiku for reasoning before potentially reaching Claude as one tier in the system. However, Claude noted that the search didn't reveal a specific conversation about Claude's own internal pre-LLM processing pipeline (such as classifiers, prompt construction, or tool handling), distinguishing between discussions of Luna's architecture that routes to Claude versus Claude's internal processing mechanisms. Claude offered to search with different keywords if the user was looking for a different conversation than the Eclissi discussion.\n\n**Tool Knowledge**\n\nThe conversation_search tool effectively located relevant discussions using broad architectural keywords like \"Claude processes LLM architecture pipeline.\" When searching for technical architecture discussions, combining the system name with process-related terms yielded relevant results even when the exact phrasing differed from the search query. The tool successfully identified the \"Eclissi Cure\" conversation which contained detailed technical discussions about tiered processing systems, demonstrating that searches for internal system architecture can surface related multi-system architectural discussions.",
